eople, on their own terms and for their own purposes. At the same time, autonomous Native groups aimed to control contact with dangerous outsiders, so as to protect their communities from threats that came in the form of sicknesses, vices, forced labor, and land invasions. Their tactical decisions shaped and limited colonizing enterprises in Brazil, while revealing Native peoples' capacity for cultural persistence through transformation. These contact strategies are preserved in the collective memories of Indigenous groups today, informing struggles for survival and self-determination in the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAutonomy. 0aIndians of South AmericaxWarszBrazil. 0aIndians, Treatment ofzBrazilxHistory. 0aWhiteszBrazilxRelations with IndiansxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh  aBrazil.  aIndigenous peoples.  aalliance.  aautonomy.  aborderlands.  acolonial legacies.  acolonialism.  acontact.  aintercultural trade.  aresistance.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362812040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503628120423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503628120/original  a978-3-11-073914-5  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles